<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">31266902</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2021</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>28</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2024</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>27</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1468-3318</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>29</Volume><Issue>3</Issue><PubDate><Year>2020</Year><Month>May</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Tobacco control</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Tob Control</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Smoke-free and tobacco-free colleges and universities in the United States.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>289</StartPage><EndPage>294</EndPage><MedlinePgn>289-294</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1136/tobaccocontrol-2018-054829</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="OBJECTIVE">To describe the number and proportion of accredited, degree-granting institutions with 100% smoke-free and 100% tobacco-free protections across the USA and by state.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS">Data on postsecondary education institutions from the US Department of Education National Center for Education Statistics Integrated Postsecondary Education Data System 2015, and smoke-free and tobacco-free campus protections from the American Nonsmokers' Rights Foundation's Smokefree and Tobacco-Free Colleges and Universities List 2017, were integrated to calculate the number and proportion of: (1) smoke-free and tobacco-free accredited, degree-granting institutions and (2) students and staff protected by campus policies and state laws. Campus protections are given a 100% smoke-free designation if smoking is not allowed on campus anywhere, at any time; 100% tobacco-free designations extend smoke-free protections to include non-combustible products such as smokeless tobacco.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS">823 accredited, degree-granting institutions (16.7%) representing 1816 individual campuses, sites and schools have either 100% smoke-free or 100% tobacco-free protections. An estimated 14.9 million college students (26.9%) and 8.9 million faculty and staff (25.4%) are protected by campus policies and state laws. Only three states and two territories have 100% smoke-free or 100% tobacco-free protections in over half of their institutions; four states and six territories have no known 100% smoke-free or 100% tobacco-free campus protections.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS">In 2017, just 16.7% of accredited, degree-granting institutions in the USA had 100% smoke-free or 100% tobacco-free protections. Despite progress, more efforts can ensure that students and staff benefit from comprehensive 100% smoke-free and 100% tobacco-free protections at US colleges and universities.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; Author(s) (or their employer(s)) 2020. No commercial re-use. See rights and permissions. Published by BMJ.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Blake</LastName><ForeName>Kelly D</ForeName><Initials>KD</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-2151-2983</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>HCIRB/BRP/DCCPS, National Cancer Institute, Bethesda, Maryland, USA kelly.blake@nih.gov.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Klein</LastName><ForeName>Amanda L</ForeName><Initials>AL</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>BLH Technologies, Inc, Rockville, Maryland, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Walpert</LastName><ForeName>Laura</ForeName><Initials>L</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>American Nonsmokers' Rights Foundation, Berkeley, California, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Casey</LastName><ForeName>Len</ForeName><Initials>L</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>American Nonsmokers' Rights Foundation, 